This week, Twitter asked for help (https://twitter.com/jack/status/96923427=
5420655616) as it tries to promote healthier conversations on the platform.=
 Yesterday, we talked with Time Well Spent movement cofounder Joe Edelman (=
https://www.getrevue.co/profile/caseynewton/issues/twitter-asks-for-help-99=
840) about his concerns that a focus on optimizing for any metric, however =
well intentioned, turns people into Tamagotchis.=C2=A0

I also reached out to Eugene Yi, president and co-founder of the nonprofit =
research group=C2=A0Cortico (https://www.cortico.ai/). Cortico, which uses =
tech tools to public conversations, has been in touch with Twitter about it=
s effort to improve the platform, and was cited in the company's request fo=
r proposals (https://blog.twitter.com/official/en_us/topics/company/2018/tw=
itter-health-metrics-proposal-submission.html) on how to gauge healthy conv=
ersations.=C2=A0

Yi agreed to answer a few questions via email about what's happening.

CASEY NEWTON: Tell me about what Cortico does. What are some projects you'v=
e worked on that speak to your main interests?

EUGENE YI: Cortico has roots in the MIT Media Lab. Several projects that po=
int to our main interests stem from research conducted at the Laboratory fo=
r Social Machines (LSM) (https://socialmachines.media.mit.edu/) in the MIT =
Media Lab.=C2=A0

LSM=E2=80=99s Electome (http://www.electome.org/) project=E2=80=93funded by=
 the Knight Foundation=E2=80=93focused on automated semantic and network an=
alysis applied to map social media conversation and news media coverage of =
the 2016 U.S. presidential election. This approach to mapping the issues pe=
ople are talking about and the news they=E2=80=99re sharing within multiple=
 domains (e.g., politics, religion, etc.) and across various tribes (e.g., =
political, cultural, ideological, geographic) will help inform LSM and Cort=
ico=E2=80=99s development of the public sphere health indicators.

To date, interest in our unique approach to mapping and analyzing public sp=
here conversation has been strong. A December VICE News piece on the Electo=
me=E2=80=99s issue/supporter networks (http://%20https://news.vice.com/stor=
y/journalists-and-trump-voters-live-in-separate-online-bubbles-mit-analysis=
-shows%20) was among the most-viewed articles in the publication=E2=80=99s =
history. The New York Times featured our filter bubble work (https://www.ny=
times.com/2017/03/03/arts/the-battle-over-your-political-bubble.html?smprod=
=3Dnytcore-iphone&amp;amp;smid=3Dnytcore-iphone-share) in a front-page stor=
y in March.

How did you come to work with Twitter on this?

Twitter became a member of the Media Lab in 2014 (http://news.mit.edu/2014/=
twitter-funds-mit-media-lab-program-1001), supporting LSM media analytics r=
esearch =E2=80=9Cto understand the role Twitter and other platforms play in=
 the way people communicate.=E2=80=9D During this time, LSM has completed m=
ultiple projects and published several papers based on Twitter data.=20

Cortico was launched as a non-profit in 2016 to scale up professional deplo=
yment of LSM media analytics R&amp;amp;D, including this public sphere heal=
th indicator work.

Finally, Deb Roy and Eugene Yi both formerly worked at Twitter. Deb=E2=80=
=99s role was the Chief Media Scientist and Eugene=E2=80=99s role was the H=
ead of Asia Public Policy. Both Eugene and Deb have stepped down from their=
 roles at Twitter and now are, alongside co-founder Russell Stevens, buildi=
ng Cortico.=20

What sort of impact does the Cortico team hope to have with Twitter?

The first step to improve our public spheres is to diagnose and measure whe=
re it is currently healthy or unhealthy. We hope that our health indicators=
 will provide Twitter and other media platforms with a useful benchmark of =
how their product affects public discourse both positively and negatively. =
Twitter=E2=80=99s commitment to increasing the collective health, openness,=
 and civility of public conversation is an important step towards this end.=
=20

I understand that Twitter is looking for a set of metrics around which to o=
ptimize for better conversations. Do you think such a metric exists? And ho=
w to you guard against the unintended consequences that have come from opti=
mizing from earlier, innocuous-seeming metrics, such as daily active users =
or time spent on site?=20

We thought this was a terrific, nuanced question that represents one of the=
 key challenges that we will need to address. Our hope is that our health i=
ndicators will reflect aspects of healthy public discourse. While the princ=
iples of shared attention, shared reality, variety, and receptivity might b=
e enduring, these metrics will require continuous evaluation and refinement=
 as the public sphere evolves. We think putting forth a first version of he=
alth indicators is a positive step forward, and recognize that what we meas=
ure and why we measure will need to progress over time.=C2=A0


